  "text": "Nonetheless, while SES did not appear to affect HRQL in our participants at the time of assessment, it is unlikely to remain unimportant over time. It has been proposed that people of lower SES face a 'double burden', namely increased health complications as well as lower HRQL when their health declines [CITATION_1] . Participants in our study were middle-aged, overweight but not obese, did not smoke, and had no significant comorbid conditions. Over time, these men may put on more weight, and adult weight gain is associated with increased risk of chronic diseases in men (De Mutsert et al., 2014) . This progression from overweight to a diseased state is more likely to occur in those of lower SES. Thus, even though our results covered a period of approximately 30 weeks, our findings may not reflect the trend over years, and over time it is likely that those of lower SES would have a larger reduction in HRQL than those who are wealthier.",
